It also asks questions about how cultural identity fits within liberal democratic states, the recognition of cultural identities and practices of minorities, and whether Indigenous groups should be distinguished from immigrant groups. This directly addresses promoting the social, economic, and political inclusion of all, irrespective of identity.

target_name: Promote the rule of law and ensure equal access to justice
justification: The course description examines the intersection of identity, politics, and governance and asks questions about how cultural identity should fit within liberal democratic states, whether nation-states have a right to protect national identity through restrictive immigration policies, and whether liberal democratic states are obliged to recognise the cultural identities and practices of minorities. This directly relates to the rule of law and ensuring equal access to justice by examining how different identities are treated within legal and political frameworks.
analysed

This directly addresses understanding and analyzing discrimination within the penal system based on gender.

This directly addresses understanding and analyzing inequalities in the administration of punishment based on race, ethnicity, and social status.

The course aims to provide students with "essential knowledge in the technology, condition monitoring, and testing techniques for high-voltage power system equipment and components" and contributes to "Engineers Australia Stage 1 Competencies" and "Targeted Graduate Capabilities" such as "The ability to apply knowledge of basic science and fundamental technologies" and "The capability to undertake challenging analysis and design problems and find optimal solutions," which are directly relevant skills for employment in the power engineering sector.

The course description explicitly states that "Large-scale electricity supply networks deliver electricity from the generating sources (e.g., power stations, wind farms, solar farms) to major load centres... This bulk transport of electricity must be carried out at high voltage... Thus, high voltage technology is an indispensable specialisation in power engineering." The course provides "essential knowledge" for "designers and operators of high-voltage equipment and power utility engineers," directly contributing to the infrastructure and expertise required for reliable and efficient electricity transmission and distribution, which is fundamental to providing access to energy services.

The course focuses on "High Voltage Systems" which are a critical part of "Large-scale electricity supply networks". It provides "detailed coverage of the common features of major items of high voltage equipment and components," "design and operation of specific items of equipment," and "condition monitoring and high-voltage diagnostic testing methods." This knowledge is essential for "designers and operators of high-voltage equipment and power utility engineers" to maintain, upgrade, and ensure the reliability of energy infrastructure.

The course description highlights the role of high voltage systems in delivering electricity to "major load centres (e.g., cities, regional areas, heavy industry)". The knowledge provided is "essential for designers and operators of high-voltage equipment and power utility engineers," who are involved in the planning and operation of the electrical infrastructure that underpins sustainable urban and regional development.

The course covers "materials used (particularly insulating materials)" in high voltage equipment and "electrical/physical/chemical diagnostic measurements for insulation assessment". Understanding the properties and condition of these materials, and techniques for assessing their degradation, is directly relevant to managing the lifecycle of high voltage equipment and potentially reducing waste and the environmental impact associated with material failure.
analysed

CLO1 states students will "Identify... approaches used to minimise an organisations water footprint". CLO4 states students will "Justify the selection of water treatment equipment and processes that enable complex and competing priorities to be satisfied, such as minimising carbon footprint while maximising discharge water quality". CLO5 states students will "Design complex, sustainable wastewater treatment processes". These learning outcomes and course content directly address upgrading industrial infrastructure and processes for sustainability, particularly concerning water use and wastewater treatment.

It then states the course covers "more efficient water use, increased recycling and more intensive treatment prior to discharge" and students will "study approaches to reduce freshwater consumption, wastewater reuse and recycling, and integration of treatment operations that enable increasingly stringent environmental regulations to be met". CLO1 states students will "Identify water intensive industrial activities and approaches used to minimise an organisations water footprint". CLO3 states students will "Apply various methods that can be used to reduce water consumption and discharge volumes... with emphasis on water pinch analysis, wastewater recycling and wastewater reuse". CLO4 states students will "Justify the selection of water treatment equipment and processes that enable... maximising discharge water quality". CLO5 states students will "Design complex, sustainable wastewater treatment processes". This focus on reducing, reusing, recycling, and treating industrial wastewater containing pollutants directly contributes to the environmentally sound management of waste.

Understanding and critically examining the reasons for this over-representation directly contributes to understanding and potentially addressing social inequalities within the criminal justice system, which is a barrier to inclusion.

CLO4 states students will "Demonstrate effective written communication skills by articulating legal concepts clearly, persuasively and appropriately" and CLO6 states students will "Demonstrate effective oral communication skills by discussing and debating course concepts in a scholarly, reflective and respectful manner". These are explicitly stated skills developed in the course that are transferable and relevant to future employment, particularly in legal or related fields.
analysed

target_name: Skills for employment, decent jobs and entrepreneurship
justification: The course outline describes learning outcomes such as "Assess the climatic factors influencing the thermal comfort of domestic architecture," "Perform a lifecycle of analysis," and "Apply strategies, systems and technologies to enhance the environmental performance," which are practical skills directly applicable to the architectural and building environment sectors, contributing to skills for employment.

target_name: Upgrade all industries and infrastructures for sustainability
justification: The course explicitly covers "design strategies and scientific understanding needed to minimise buildings’ impact on natural resources and the environment," "life-cycle thinking in architectural design," and "techniques to reduce building-related carbon emissions," which directly contribute to upgrading infrastructure for sustainability.

target_name: Support least developed countries, including through financial and technical assistance, in building sustainable and resilient buildings utilizing local materials
justification: While not specifically focused on least developed countries, the course's emphasis on "design strategies and scientific understanding needed to minimise buildings’ impact on natural resources and the environment," "responding to climate," and "climate-sensitive design" provides technical knowledge applicable to building sustainable and resilient buildings, which is a core component of this target.

target_name: Sustainable management and efficient use of natural resources
justification: The course explicitly covers "design strategies and scientific understanding needed to minimise buildings’ impact on natural resources," "life-cycle thinking in architectural design," and "Embodied Carbon and Material Sustainability," directly addressing the sustainable management and efficient use of natural resources in the built environment.

target_name: Strengthen the prevention and treatment of substance abuse, including narcotic drug abuse and harmful use of alcohol.
justification: The course explicitly states a learning outcome (CLO4) to "Identify key mental health issues prevalent in this group and their impact on offending, culpability and the risk of reoffending." While not solely focused on substance abuse, mental health issues are often intertwined with substance abuse in criminal populations, and understanding these issues is a step towards prevention and treatment within the context of serious offenders.

target_name: Skills for employment, decent jobs and entrepreneurship
justification: The course description states it is "aimed at those with a general interest in the forensic area who may wish to pursue a professional career or research in this fascinating field" and complements existing professional degrees. This explicitly links the course content to developing skills relevant for professional careers in fields related to the justice system.

target_name: Promote the rule of law at the national and international levels and ensure equal access to justice for all.
justification: The course aims include understanding "the investigation of serious criminal offending, treatment of serious offenders, and incarceration" and identifying "the major issues involved in the investigation, prosecution, and punishment of serious offenders" (CLO2). It also provides insights into "various professional groups associated with the justice system such as the police, forensic psychiatrists, pathologists, custodial administrators, and criminal lawyers." This directly addresses understanding the institutions and processes of the justice system and the rule of law in the context of serious crime.
analysed

target_name: Reduce deaths and illnesses from hazardous chemicals and pollution
justification: The course focuses on "Safety Management Systems" in "highly hazardous environment[s]" including "aviation, nuclear, and oil and gas," aiming to achieve "minimal risk." This directly contributes to reducing deaths and illnesses associated with these hazardous environments by improving safety protocols.

The course aims to "equip the student with the theoretical knowledge of the requirements of a SMS" and the "knowledge and skills necessary to undertake the functions and responsibilities of a Safety Manager," which are explicitly stated as preparing students for employment in relevant industries.

target_name: Develop quality, reliable, sustainable and resilient infrastructure
justification: The course focuses on "Safety Management Systems" in "aviation transport systems" and other "high reliability industries," which are integral components of infrastructure. By improving safety and reliability, the course directly contributes to developing more resilient infrastructure.

target_name: Develop effective, accountable and transparent institutions
justification: The course focuses on understanding and implementing Safety Management Systems as described by international (ICAO) and domestic (CASA Australia) requirements. This directly contributes to developing more effective and accountable institutions within the aviation sector by promoting standardized safety protocols and regulatory compliance.
analysed

target_name: Support the research and development of vaccines and medicines for the communicable and non-communicable diseases that primarily affect developing countries, provide access to affordable essential medicines and vaccines, in accordance with the Doha Declaration on the TRIPS Agreement and Public Health, which affirms the right of developing countries to use to the full the provisions in the Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights regarding flexibilities to protect public health, and, in particular, provide for access to medicines for all.
justification: The course description explicitly states "Computer modelling of complex physiological systems and their interaction with medical devices is becoming increasingly important in modern medical device design" and focuses on applications including "electrical stimulation of neural and cardiac tissue, implantable drug delivery, cancer therapy, biomechanics and blood flow," which directly supports the research and development aspects related to health interventions.

target_name: By 2030, substantially increase the number of youth and adults who have relevant skills, including technical and vocational skills, for employment, decent jobs and entrepreneurship.
justification: The course aims to provide a "practical overview of computational modelling in bioengineering" and teaches "basic principles of modelling and simulation" using software like "Matlab and COMSOL Multiphysics," which are technical skills directly relevant for employment in the biomedical engineering field.

target_name: Enhance scientific research, upgrade the technological capabilities of industrial sectors in all countries, in particular developing countries, including, by 2030, encouraging innovation and substantially increasing the number of research and development workers per 1 million people and public and private research and development spending.
justification: The course focuses on "Computer modelling of complex physiological systems and their interaction with medical devices" and provides a "practical overview of computational modelling in bioengineering," explicitly stating its importance in "modern medical device design" and "improving overall device design," which directly contributes to enhancing scientific research and technological capabilities in the biomedical sector.

The course description explicitly states the aim is to teach students "how one can change their lifestyle in subtle ways to live a healthier life" and the course aims include exploring "how the body stores energy when in excess, leading to weight gain, and how the body uses energy in times of deficiency like exercise, fasting or starvation, leading to weight loss." This directly addresses the prevention and control of non-communicable diseases linked to weight and lifestyle.

target_name: Skills for employment, decent jobs and entrepreneurship
justification: The outline states "Our ultimate goal is to provide the students with a set of tools to comprehend and address problems, particularly oceanographic ones" and lists learning outcomes like "define, analyse, and solve problems relating the force balances that drive the large-scale ocean circulation" and "describe and solve problems relating to the role of turbulence in mixing water properties and momentum in the ocean," which directly contribute to developing specialized skills relevant for employment in oceanography or related fields.

The course description and aims explicitly state the examination of "the dynamics of large-scale wind-driven ocean currents" and "The production of turbulence in the oceans and its role in mixing is also examined." Understanding these processes is fundamental to protecting and restoring marine ecosystems, as ocean circulation and mixing directly influence the distribution of nutrients, temperature, and pollutants, which are critical for marine life and ecosystem health.

The course description explicitly states "This course provides a theoretical background to chemistry in an environmental aquatic context" and the course aims include "Knowledge of the fundamental and applied environmental chemistry as they may be encountered by environmental engineers". The course learning outcomes include the ability to "Use practical tools to solve environmental problems and quantify processes" related to environmental chemistry. This directly supports improving water quality by providing the foundational knowledge and tools to understand and address chemical processes in aquatic environments.

The course description focuses on "chemistry in an environmental aquatic context" and includes topics such as "equilibrium, kinetics, acid-base reactions, alkalinity, carbonate chemistry, gas exchange, redox chemistry, complexes, solid precipitation and dissolution, surface chemistry and organic carbon chemistry". The computer lab exercises include topics like "Uranium in seawater", "Carbonate Chemistry", "Photosynthesis", "Mixing and redox", "Metal complexation", "Common ion effect", "Trace element adsorption on iron-oxide surfaces", and "Organic carbon interaction with metals". This explicit focus on the chemical processes occurring in aquatic environments, including seawater, directly contributes to understanding and potentially mitigating marine pollution by providing the scientific basis for analyzing and addressing the chemical impacts of pollutants.
analysed

target_name: Skills for employment, decent jobs and entrepreneurship
justification: The course aims to provide students with "hands-on application to practical engineering design" and covers "Engineering design considerations including beach nourishment and the design of standard coastal structures", directly contributing to developing skills relevant for employment in coastal engineering.

target_name: Develop quality, reliable, sustainable and resilient infrastructure
justification: The course explicitly covers "practical engineering design of breakwaters, seawalls, piles, decks, and marinas" and "design of standard coastal structures", directly contributing to the development of resilient infrastructure.

target_name: Reduce the adverse per capita environmental impact of cities, including by paying special attention to air quality and municipal and other waste management
justification: The course covers "coastal hazards" and "the impact of coastal storms on the beaches", and includes "Engineering design considerations including beach nourishment and the design of standard coastal structures", which are relevant to reducing the environmental impact of coastal communities and increasing their resilience to hazards.

target_name: Strengthen resilience and adaptive capacity to climate-related hazards and natural disasters in all countries
justification: The course explicitly includes "Coastal and beach processes are introduced, including tides, storms, currents and elevated water levels, beach morphology, coastal hazards" and "the impact of coastal storms on the beaches", and covers "practical engineering design of breakwaters, seawalls... and marinas", directly addressing the need to strengthen resilience to climate-related hazards.

target_name: Sustainably manage and protect marine and coastal ecosystems to avoid significant adverse impacts, including by strengthening their resilience, and take action for their restoration in order to achieve healthy and productive oceans
justification: The course focuses on "Coastal Engineering", covering "how waves are formed, grow, travel across the ocean, shoaling and refraction as they enter shallower coastal waters and eventual wave breaking at the beach", "fundamental sediment transports due to waves and currents", "beach morphology", and "Engineering design considerations including beach nourishment and the design of standard coastal structures", all of which are directly relevant to understanding and managing coastal ecosystems.
analysed

The course aims state students will "gain a professional understanding" of engineering concepts related to Rivers, Estuaries, and Wetlands, and Course Learning Outcome 3 is to "Synthesise and interpret available data for river and estuary systems to compose a high-quality engineering report", which directly contributes to developing skills for employment in relevant engineering fields.

The course explicitly covers "Water Quality Modelling" and "biochemical processes in estuaries", and Course Learning Outcome 5 is to "Solve water quality and dispersion problems using numerical models and empirical equations for pollutant dispersion and river flow", directly contributing to the protection and restoration of water-related ecosystems.

The course schedule explicitly includes a lecture on "Hydrodynamic Modelling and Climate Change Impacts" and refers to a webpage regarding "Estuaries and climate change", directly contributing to understanding and potentially building resilience to climate-related impacts.

The course focuses on "Estuaries" and "Wetlands", including "estuarine classification and density structure; tides, water level response, mixing processes and flushing of estuaries; estuarine difference models including hydrodynamic stratification and algal dynamics; random walk and box models; biochemical processes in estuaries", and "wetland design, restoration and rehabilitation", directly contributing to the sustainable management and protection of marine and coastal ecosystems.

target_name: Conserve and restore terrestrial and inland freshwater ecosystems
justification: The course focuses on "Rivers" and "Wetlands", including "River Geomorphology; River Engineering and Management" and "wetland design, restoration and rehabilitation", directly contributing to the conservation and restoration of inland freshwater ecosystems.
